2025-11-11 19:59:23 (546 KB/s) - ‘1661-0.txt’ saved [607504/607504]

6. Changing Permissions
Create a file named secure.txt and change its permissions to read-only for everyone using chmod.
[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$ chmod 444 secure.txt
[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$ ll
total 604
-r--r--r--. 1 sreejithr sreejithr     16 Nov 11 20:00 secure.txt


7. Working with Environment Variables
Use export to set a new environment variable called MY_VAR with the value "Hello, Linux!".

[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$ MY_VAR='Hello'
[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$ echo $MY_VAR
Hello
[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$ export MY_VAR
[sreejithr@localhost linuxcommandslearn]$

